Pyang version: 1.7.3
Python version: 3.5

When parsing the following yang snippet:
```
module test {
	yang-version 1.1;
	namespace "http://www.example.com/test";
	prefix test;
	container a {
		leaf isAnInteger {
			type int16;
			default 0x1234;
		}
	}
}
```
pyang complains with the following output message:

```
test.yang:8: error: the value "0x1234" does not match its base type - not an integer
```

This is not correct since, based on RFC7950 (Yang 1.1) 9.2.1 Lexical Representation, the hexadecimal format "0xabcd" is allowed to express the default value associated to an integer type (uint8, uint16, uint32, uint64, int8, int16, int32, int64). The parsing should then be successful

The previous releases of pyang (e.g. pyang 1.7.1) did not generate this error, so this appears to be a regression. Please note that the hexadecimal notation is widely used also in IETF modules (e.g. ietf-ptp-dataset.yang module) as a convenient way to express default values for integers.

The same error is also returned if the octal notation is used:

```
module test {
	yang-version 1.1;
	namespace "http://www.example.com/test";
	prefix test;
	container a {
		leaf isAnInteger {
			type int16;
			default 052;
		}
	}
}
```

Expected behaviour:
pyang shall accept as valid hexadecimal and octal notation for default values assigned to "integer" types, according to RFC7950 9.2.1

This check at line 1851 in `statements.py` should only be made for 1.1 - this is valid in 1.

